  "correctAnswer": "Write a persuasive product description that focuses on benefits rather than features. For every feature the product has, translate it into a real-world benefit that the customer will actually feel or experience in their daily life — do not just list what the product does, explain what it means for the customer. For example, instead of saying 'has a 5000mAh battery', say 'lasts all day so you never have to worry about finding a charger'. The description should speak directly to the customer's desires, frustrations, or goals — make them feel like this product was designed to solve a problem they face every day. Use warm, confident, and persuasive language throughout. Keep the description between 100 to 150 words — long enough to be convincing but short enough to hold attention on a product page.",
  "explanation": "The single biggest mistake people make when writing product descriptions is listing features instead of benefits. Features tell the customer what a product has — benefits tell the customer what it does for them. These are very different things, and only one of them actually convinces someone to buy. By specifically instructing the AI to translate every feature into a real-world benefit, this prompt forces the output to be customer-focused rather than product-focused. The battery example in the prompt is intentional — giving the AI a concrete before-and-after example of a feature versus a benefit teaches it exactly what kind of transformation you are looking for in the language. The word limit of 100 to 150 words keeps the description tight and suitable for an e-commerce product page where customers are scanning quickly and need to be convinced fast."
