  "keywords": "REST API, Node.js, validation, error handling",
  "correctAnswer": "Write a REST API endpoint in Node.js using Express. The endpoint should accept a POST request that takes a user's name, email, and password as inputs. Add input validation that checks whether all three fields are present, whether the email is in a valid format, and whether the password is at least 8 characters long — if any of these checks fail, return a clear and descriptive error message with the appropriate HTTP status code so the developer knows exactly what went wrong. If all inputs are valid, return a success response with a 200 status code and a confirmation message. Include proper error handling for unexpected server errors as well, and return a 500 status code with a generic error message in those cases so sensitive server details are never exposed to the client. Add clear comments throughout the code explaining what each section does so a beginner developer can read and understand it easily.",
  "explanation": "When asking the AI to generate code, vague prompts produce vague and often unusable results. Specifying the exact technology — Node.js with Express — tells the AI which framework and syntax to use so the code works straight away without needing to be rewritten. Defining the exact input fields — name, email, and password — gives the AI a concrete example to work with rather than writing generic placeholder code that still needs to be customized before it can be used. The validation rules are the most important part of this prompt because without them, the AI might write a working endpoint that accepts any input including empty fields or invalid emails, which would create serious bugs and security vulnerabilities in a real application. Asking for specific HTTP status codes — 400 for bad input and 500 for server errors — ensures the API follows industry-standard practices that other developers will expect and understand. The instruction to add comments throughout the code is especially important for a beginner audience because code without explanations is very hard to learn from, even if it works perfectly."
