  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "refactor, performance, readability",
  "correctAnswer": "Refactor the following function to improve both performance and readability. Focus on reducing unnecessary loops or repeated computations by using more efficient logic or built-in methods where possible. Rename any vague variable or function names to descriptive ones that clearly communicate their purpose. Break down large or complex blocks of code into smaller, well-named helper functions so each part of the code does exactly one thing. Remove any redundant or duplicate code and replace it with reusable logic. Add concise comments wherever the logic is not immediately obvious so another developer can understand the intent without having to trace through every line. The refactored function should produce the exact same output as the original — do not change its behavior, only improve how it is written and how efficiently it runs.",
  "explanation": "Refactoring prompts fail when they are too vague because the AI does not know which dimension of improvement to prioritize — it might rename a few variables and call it done, or it might rewrite the entire function in a way that changes its behavior. Specifying both performance and readability as separate goals forces the AI to address both concerns explicitly rather than treating them as the same thing. Asking for reduction of unnecessary loops and repeated computations gives the AI a concrete direction for performance improvement instead of leaving it to guess what inefficiency exists. Requiring descriptive variable and function names is critical because poorly named code is one of the most common readability problems, and without this instruction the AI may keep the original names even when refactoring. The instruction to break large blocks into smaller helper functions ensures the AI does not just clean up the surface of the code but actually improves its structure and modularity. Most importantly, explicitly stating that the output must remain identical prevents the AI from accidentally introducing bugs while refactoring, which is a very common failure when the prompt does not make behavioral preservation a hard requirement."
