  "id": "c_p10",
  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Design a prompt that explains a complex algorithm in simple terms for junior developers.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "explain algorithm, simple terms, junior developers",
  "correctAnswer": "Explain the following algorithm in simple, beginner-friendly terms for a junior developer who understands basic programming concepts but has never encountered this algorithm before. Start with a one or two sentence plain-English summary of what the algorithm does and why it is useful. Then walk through how it works step by step, using a small and concrete example with actual values so the reader can follow along without getting lost in abstraction. Avoid using technical jargon without explanation — if a term like recursion or time complexity must be used, briefly define it in simple words before moving on. After the step-by-step walkthrough, mention one real-world scenario where this algorithm is commonly used so the junior developer understands its practical value. End with a note on its time and space complexity using plain language, such as explaining what happens to the speed of the algorithm as the input grows larger, without assuming the reader already knows Big O notation.",
  "explanation": "Vague explanation prompts like 'explain this simply' often produce responses that are still too technical because the AI does not know the baseline knowledge level of the audience. Specifying that the reader is a junior developer who knows basic programming but has never seen this algorithm gives the AI a precise starting point so it does not over-explain basics like what a variable is, but also does not skip over concepts like recursion without defining them. Asking for a plain-English summary first ensures the developer gets the big picture before diving into details, which is how humans learn most effectively — context before complexity. Requiring a concrete example with actual values is one of the most important instructions because abstract algorithmic explanations without examples are extremely hard to follow for beginners, and the AI will often skip examples unless explicitly told to include them. The instruction to define jargon before using it prevents the explanation from feeling like it assumes knowledge the junior developer does not yet have, which is the most common reason technical explanations fail their intended audience. Including a real-world use case grounds the algorithm in practical relevance, which helps junior developers understand why they should care about learning it. Finally, asking for complexity explained in plain language rather than Big O notation ensures the developer walks away with a useful mental model of performance without being overwhelmed by mathematical notation they may not yet understand."
