  "correctAnswer": "Explain Big-O notation to a complete beginner who understands basic programming concepts like loops and functions but has never studied algorithms or time complexity before. Start with a plain-English explanation of what Big-O notation is and why developers use it — focus on the idea that it describes how the speed or memory usage of a program changes as the size of the input grows, without using any mathematical symbols in the opening explanation. Then introduce the most common Big-O complexities one at a time in order from fastest to slowest — O(1), O(log n), O(n), O(n log n), and O(n²) — and for each one provide a simple real-world analogy first, followed by a short code example in JavaScript that clearly demonstrates that complexity. After each code example, explain in one or two sentences why that code belongs to that complexity class so the beginner understands the reasoning and not just the label. Avoid using formal mathematical notation like summations or limits anywhere in the explanation. End with a simple comparison table that lists each complexity, its plain-English meaning, and a one-line example so the beginner has a quick reference they can return to. Use an encouraging and patient tone throughout so the topic feels approachable rather than intimidating.",
  "explanation": "A vague prompt like 'explain Big-O notation with examples for beginners' often produces a response that still uses mathematical language and formal definitions that are completely inaccessible to someone who has never studied algorithms. Specifying that the audience understands loops and functions but has never encountered time complexity gives the AI a precise knowledge baseline so it does not over-explain what a variable is, but also does not assume the reader already knows what logarithms mean. Starting with a plain-English explanation before introducing any symbols is critical because Big-O notation looks intimidating to beginners and jumping straight into O(n) or O(log n) without context causes most readers to disengage immediately. Asking for complexities to be introduced one at a time in order from fastest to slowest gives the explanation a clear and logical structure that builds understanding progressively rather than overwhelming the reader with all complexities at once. Requiring a real-world analogy before each code example is one of the most important instructions because analogies create mental models that make abstract concepts stick — without them, the beginner may understand the code example but still not grasp what the complexity class actually means in practice. Specifying JavaScript for the code examples ensures the output is consistent and uses a language that most beginners are already familiar with, rather than the AI switching between languages unpredictably. The instruction to explain why each code example belongs to its complexity class is essential because without it the AI often just labels the example without helping the reader develop the reasoning skills to classify code on their own in the future. Explicitly banning formal mathematical notation like summations and limits prevents the explanation from becoming a math lecture, which is the most common reason Big-O explanations fail their beginner audience. Asking for a summary comparison table at the end gives the beginner a practical reference tool they can use while coding, making the explanation immediately useful beyond just reading it once. Finally, specifying an encouraging and patient tone ensures the AI does not accidentally make the topic feel more complex or exclusive than it needs to be, which is especially important for beginners who may already feel intimidated by algorithm topics."
