  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Write a prompt that converts a callback-based function to async/await syntax.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "convert callback, async/await, refactor",
  "correctAnswer": "Convert the following callback-based function to modern async/await syntax in JavaScript. Start by identifying every callback in the original function and replacing it with a Promise-based equivalent using async and await so the code reads sequentially from top to bottom like synchronous code. Wrap the entire function body in a try/catch block so that any asynchronous errors that would have been handled by the callback's error argument are now caught and handled gracefully in one place. If the original function uses nested callbacks — commonly known as callback hell — make sure the converted version eliminates all nesting and instead awaits each asynchronous operation one at a time in a clean, flat structure. Do not change the logic or behavior of the function in any way — the converted version must produce exactly the same result as the original for all inputs. If any part of the original callback structure cannot be directly converted to async/await without a wrapper, use the built-in util.promisify utility or wrap it manually in a new Promise and explain in a comment why that step was necessary. Add a short comment above each awaited call explaining what that line is doing so a developer unfamiliar with the original callback version can follow the converted code without needing to refer back to the original.",
  "explanation": "A vague prompt like 'convert the following callback-based function to async/await' often produces a superficial conversion where the AI adds async and await keywords but leaves the underlying callback structure partially intact, resulting in code that mixes both patterns and is harder to read than either the original or a proper conversion. Explicitly asking the AI to identify every callback and replace it with a Promise-based equivalent ensures the entire function is converted consistently rather than only the most obvious parts. Requiring a try/catch block is one of the most critical instructions because callback-based functions handle errors through the first argument of the callback — typically called err — and if this error handling is not explicitly migrated to try/catch, the converted async/await version will silently swallow errors and make debugging extremely difficult. Addressing nested callbacks specifically is essential because callback hell — deeply nested callbacks that are hard to read and maintain — is the primary reason developers want to convert to async/await in the first place, and without this instruction the AI may convert each callback individually without flattening the nesting structure. The instruction to preserve the original behavior exactly is a hard requirement that prevents the AI from accidentally optimizing or restructuring the logic in ways that change what the function does, which is a very common failure when the prompt does not make behavioral preservation explicit. Mentioning util.promisify and manual Promise wrapping handles the real-world scenario where some Node.js APIs or third-party libraries do not natively support Promises and cannot be directly awaited without an intermediate step — skipping this instruction would cause the AI to either ignore these cases or produce code that throws runtime errors. Finally, asking for comments above each awaited call makes the converted function self-documenting and helps developers who are learning async/await understand the one-to-one relationship between the old callback structure and the new syntax, which accelerates their understanding of both patterns."
