  "text": "Write a prompt that generates insights from monthly revenue data including trends and anomalies.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "monthly revenue, trends, anomalies, insights",
  "correctAnswer": "Analyze the following monthly revenue data and generate a structured set of business insights covering trends, anomalies, and actionable recommendations. Start with a brief executive summary of two to three sentences that captures the overall revenue trajectory across the entire period so a business stakeholder can understand the big picture without reading the full analysis. Then identify and describe the overall trend — whether revenue is growing, declining, or flat — and calculate the percentage change from the first month to the last month to give the trend a concrete numerical anchor. Next, identify the single best performing month and the single worst performing month, state their exact values, and explain what might have caused those peaks and troughs based on patterns visible in the data such as seasonal spikes or sudden drops. Detect any anomalies — months where revenue deviated significantly from the expected trend, either unusually high or unusually low — and for each anomaly clearly state which month it occurred, by how much it deviated from the surrounding months, and whether it appears to be a one-time spike or the beginning of a sustained shift. Calculate the month-over-month growth rate for each consecutive pair of months and highlight the three largest positive and three largest negative changes so the reader can see where momentum accelerated or reversed most sharply. End with at least three specific and actionable business recommendations based directly on the patterns identified in the data — each recommendation should reference the specific months or trends that support it so the advice feels grounded in evidence rather than generic.",
  "explanation": "A vague prompt like 'generate insights from monthly revenue data including trends and anomalies' almost always produces a generic summary that restates the numbers without offering any genuine analytical depth — the AI might note that revenue went up in some months and down in others without explaining why, quantifying the changes, or connecting the observations to actionable business decisions. Starting with an executive summary is critical because in a real business context, stakeholders like executives and investors need to grasp the overall picture immediately without wading through detailed analysis, and without this instruction the AI typically buries the most important takeaway somewhere in the middle of the response. Requiring the percentage change from first to last month gives the trend a concrete numerical anchor that makes it immediately comparable across different time periods and datasets, whereas a vague description like 'revenue grew steadily' is too imprecise to be useful in a business report. Asking for the best and worst performing months with exact values forces the AI to engage with the specific data rather than speaking in generalities, and prompting it to suggest possible causes for those peaks and troughs pushes the analysis beyond simple description into genuine interpretation. The anomaly detection instruction is one of the most important parts of this prompt because anomalies are often the most actionable signals in revenue data — a sudden spike might indicate a successful campaign worth repeating, while an unexpected drop might signal a problem that needs immediate attention — and without explicit instructions the AI frequently glosses over anomalies or fails to distinguish them from normal variation. Asking for month-over-month growth rates for every consecutive pair of months and highlighting the largest changes gives the reader a granular view of momentum shifts that a simple overall trend line would completely hide, which is especially valuable for identifying exactly when a growth acceleration or reversal began. Finally, requiring at least three specific recommendations that reference the actual months and trends in the data is essential because the entire value of a data analysis is the decisions it enables — without this instruction the AI often ends with vague suggestions like 'continue monitoring revenue' that provide no real guidance to the business."
