    {
  "id": "b_p10",
  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Create a prompt that generates a professional client follow-up email.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "professional, email, client follow-up",
  "correctAnswer": "Write a professional and warm client follow-up email from a B2B software sales representative to a potential enterprise client who attended a product demonstration three days ago, expressed genuine interest in the platform during the meeting, but has not yet responded to the initial thank-you email sent the same day as the demo. The email is intended to re-engage the client, address any lingering hesitation, and move the conversation toward a defined next step without applying pressure that could damage the relationship or cause the client to disengage entirely — so the tone must strike a careful balance between confident and consultative, making it clear the representative is following up because they genuinely believe the product is the right fit for the client's needs rather than simply chasing a sales quota. Structure the email into five concise sections with no section exceeding three sentences — the subject line, the opening, the value reinforcement, the objection anticipation, and the call to action — and keep the total email length under two hundred words because enterprise decision-makers receive dozens of vendor emails daily and a long follow-up email signals that the sender does not respect the recipient's time. Write the subject line so it references something specific from the demo conversation rather than using a generic phrase like 'Following up on our meeting' — a subject line that references a specific pain point the client mentioned or a specific feature they reacted positively to during the demo has a significantly higher open rate than a generic follow-up subject line because it signals to the recipient that this email contains something personally relevant rather than a templated mass communication. Open the email by referencing one specific moment, question, or reaction from the demo that demonstrated the client's genuine interest — this personalization signals that the representative was listening carefully during the meeting and views the client as an individual rather than a pipeline entry, which is one of the most effective trust-building techniques in enterprise sales. In the value reinforcement section, remind the client of the single most relevant benefit the platform offers for their specific use case — connect it directly to a business challenge or goal the client mentioned during the demo rather than listing generic product features, because a benefit that solves a problem the client already acknowledged having is far more persuasive than an abstract capability description. In the objection anticipation section, proactively acknowledge one common hesitation that enterprise clients at this stage of the sales process typically have — such as concerns about implementation complexity, integration with existing systems, or internal approval processes — and briefly address it in one to two sentences that reduce friction without overwhelming the client with unsolicited information. Close with a single clear and low-commitment call to action that proposes one specific next step — such as a thirty-minute call to answer any remaining questions or a customized ROI summary document tailored to the client's industry — and include two specific date and time options to reduce the friction of scheduling rather than asking the client to propose a time themselves.",
  "explanation": "A vague prompt like 'generate a professional client follow-up email' almost always produces a generic, templated email that could have been sent to any client after any meeting — typically opening with 'I hope this email finds you well,' referencing 'our recent conversation' without any specifics, listing three to five generic product benefits, and closing with 'please let me know if you have any questions' — which is precisely the kind of email that enterprise decision-makers immediately recognize as a mass template and deprioritize or delete without responding. Specifying the exact sales context — a B2B software representative following up with an enterprise client three days after a product demo who expressed interest but has not responded to the initial thank-you — gives the AI a concrete situation with real stakes, a clear timeline, and a specific relationship dynamic that fundamentally changes the strategy, tone, and content of the email compared to a generic follow-up. Defining the dual goal of re-engaging the client and moving toward a next step without applying pressure is a critical strategic instruction because these two goals are in genuine tension — an email that is too assertive about closing risks damaging the relationship with an enterprise client who is still in an internal evaluation process, while an email that is too passive fails to advance the sales conversation and allows the opportunity to go cold — and without explicit guidance on navigating this tension the AI defaults to either an uncomfortably pushy sales email or an overly deferential message that gives the client no reason to respond. Requiring the total email to stay under two hundred words is one of the most practically important constraints in this prompt because email length is inversely correlated with response rate in enterprise sales — a long follow-up email signals either that the sender has not respected the recipient's time enough to edit ruthlessly, or that they are compensating for a weak value proposition with volume of words, and either interpretation reduces the likelihood of a response. Requiring the subject line to reference something specific from the demo rather than using a generic follow-up phrase is a critical open-rate instruction because the subject line is the only part of the email the client sees before deciding whether to open it — a generic subject line like 'Following up on our meeting' competes with dozens of identical subject lines in the client's inbox, while a subject line that references their specific pain point or a feature they reacted to during the demo creates an immediate sense of personal relevance that generic subject lines cannot achieve. The opening personalization instruction — referencing a specific moment or reaction from the demo — is one of the most strategically important elements of the entire email because enterprise clients are acutely sensitive to whether a vendor views them as an individual with specific needs or as a generic sales opportunity, and a single specific reference that demonstrates the representative was genuinely listening during the demo does more to build trust and differentiate from competitors than any number of generic relationship-building phrases. Requiring the value reinforcement section to connect the product's benefit to a specific business challenge the client mentioned rather than listing generic features reflects the fundamental principle of consultative selling — a benefit that solves a problem the client has already acknowledged having requires no persuasion because the client's own words have already established the need, whereas an abstract capability that has not been connected to a specific client problem requires the client to do additional cognitive work to understand why it matters to them, which significantly reduces the likelihood of engagement. The objection anticipation instruction is essential because the most common reason enterprise clients go silent after a demo is not that they lost interest but that an unaddressed concern — typically about implementation complexity, integration risk, or internal approval processes — has created enough uncertainty that moving forward feels risky, and proactively acknowledging and briefly addressing the most likely hesitation removes a barrier to response without requiring the client to voice the objection themselves, which many enterprise buyers are reluctant to do in writing. Finally, requiring the call to action to propose two specific date and time options rather than asking the client to propose a time is a seemingly small but practically significant instruction — asking 'please let me know when you are available' transfers the scheduling burden to the client and adds friction that reduces response rates, while proposing two specific options requires only a one-word reply of confirmation, which is the smallest possible commitment the client needs to make to advance the conversation and dramatically increases the probability that the follow-up email generates a response."
}
