  "id": "f_f24",
  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Write a prompt that generates a product description for a sustainable cotton summer dress.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "product description, sustainable cotton, summer dress",
  "correctAnswer": "Write a product description for the Solana Dress, a midi-length summer dress made from GOTS-certified organic cotton voile, sold by Haven, an independent womenswear brand whose online store targets women aged 26 to 42 who buy slowly and deliberately, care about fiber provenance without wanting to be lectured about it, and make purchase decisions based on how a garment will actually fit into their existing wardrobe rather than how it photographs on a model. The dress has a relaxed A-line silhouette, adjustable spaghetti straps, a smocked elasticated back panel that fits sizes 6 to 18 without separate sizing, two side pockets deep enough for a phone, and is available in three colorways — washed terracotta, pale sage, and natural ecru — each achieved through low-impact fiber-reactive dyes. The description must be 180 to 220 words in a single unbroken paragraph, written in second person that speaks directly to the reader without being presumptuous about her life or body, and must communicate the dress's material quality and ethical provenance in language that treats those attributes as natural facts rather than virtuous achievements, because Haven's customer has chosen the brand precisely because it does not moralize about sustainability and she will feel condescended to by any copy that frames her purchase as an act of environmental heroism. The description must open with a sensory or physical detail about the fabric or the wearing experience rather than with the dress's name or a declarative statement about what it is, must mention the smocked back's fit range in a way that feels inclusive without drawing attention to itself as an inclusion statement, must name the GOTS certification and the low-impact dye process once each in passing rather than as headline claims, and must close with a sentence about the three colorways that makes the reader want to see all of them rather than simply listing their names.",

  "explanation": "A vague prompt like 'write a product description for a sustainable cotton summer dress' produces a paragraph that opens with 'Introducing our beautiful sustainable summer dress' and closes with 'feel good about your purchase knowing it is kind to the planet,' deploying the full vocabulary of sustainable fashion copywriting — conscious, ethical, eco-friendly, planet-loving — in a register so familiar to the target customer that it functions as a signal to stop reading rather than to keep going, because a woman who has been buying sustainable fashion for five years has developed strong immunity to copy that performs environmental virtue rather than describing a garment. Naming the product the Solana Dress, specifying its GOTS-certified organic cotton voile construction, smocked back panel, size range, pocket depth, and three specific colorways achieved through low-impact fiber-reactive dyes is the foundational instruction because product description copy cannot be specific without specific product facts to work from, and a prompt that leaves the garment undefined produces a description that sounds like it could apply to any dress in any sustainable brand's summer collection. The instruction to write in second person that speaks directly to the reader without being presumptuous about her life or body is a voice discipline instruction that addresses one of the most common failures in fashion copywriting — the assumption that the customer's life can be scripted around the product, producing copy like 'perfect for beach days, rooftop parties, and weekend farmers markets' that alienates any reader whose life does not match that specific fantasy. The instruction to treat sustainability credentials as natural facts rather than virtuous achievements is the single most strategically important creative constraint in the prompt because it reflects a genuine shift in how the most discerning sustainable fashion customers respond to brand communication — a customer who has self-selected into a brand called Haven because it does not moralize will read copy that frames her purchase as an act of environmental heroism as a breach of the implicit contract she believed she was entering, and that breach will cost the brand her trust more surely than any product flaw would. Requiring the description to open with a sensory detail rather than the product name or a declarative statement is a structural instruction that reflects how purchase decisions are actually made for tactile products like clothing — a reader who is told what a dress is before she is made to feel what it would be like to wear it is being asked to evaluate an abstract object rather than imagine a lived experience, and the imagination of a lived experience is what converts a browser into a buyer."
