    "type": "prompt-writing",
    "text": "Design a prompt that creates a public health awareness message about flu prevention.",
    "options": [],
    "correctIndex": -1,
    "keywords": "public health awareness, flu prevention",
    "correctAnswer": "Write a public health awareness message about flu prevention for display on digital screens in the waiting areas of six GP practices in a South London NHS Primary Care Network serving a demographically mixed population that includes a high proportion of residents over 65, a significant South Asian community, and a large number of working-age adults with young children — to be displayed from the first week of October through the end of February during the influenza season, rotating with other public health messages on a 25-second display cycle, meaning the message must communicate its core call to action within the first three seconds of a distracted viewer's attention before the screen changes, and must be compelling enough that a patient who has seen it three times in the waiting room still notices it on the fourth viewing rather than filtering it out as visual wallpaper. Write three versions of the message for three distinct audience segments who share the waiting room but have different motivations for getting or not getting the flu vaccine: the first version targets adults over 65 for whom the flu vaccine is strongly recommended and free, whose primary barrier to vaccination is often complacency rather than opposition — they have had mild flu before and survived, and do not perceive themselves as high-risk despite being in the highest-risk group; the second version targets parents of young children, whose motivation is protecting their child rather than themselves and who may not know that children aged two to seventeen are eligible for the free nasal spray vaccine at the GP practice; and the third version targets working-age adults who are not in a clinical risk group and are therefore not eligible for a free NHS vaccine but who can access it at a pharmacy for approximately twelve pounds, whose primary barrier is the belief that flu is just a bad cold and that the vaccine is not worth the cost or the minor inconvenience. Each version must be no more than 40 words of body text with a headline of no more than six words, must include one specific and memorable fact that contradicts the most common misconception held by that audience segment, must make the call to action — whether to book a vaccine appointment, ask at reception, or visit a pharmacy — explicit and immediate rather than general and aspirational, and must not use the word important, the phrase protect yourself or your family, or any statistic expressed as a percentage without also expressing it as a plain-English equivalent, because percentages are consistently misread by low-health-literacy audiences in ways that either overstate or understate risk depending on the individual's numeracy level.",

    "explanation": "A vague prompt like 'generate a public health awareness message about flu prevention' produces a single generic poster that opens with 'Flu season is here — protect yourself and your loved ones' and closes with 'Get your free flu vaccine today — ask at reception,' a message so familiar from twenty years of NHS waiting room posters that the target audience has developed complete immunity to it through repeated exposure and processes it as background noise rather than as actionable health communication. Specifying the display context as a 25-second rotating digital screen in a South London GP waiting room serving an over-65 population, a South Asian community, and parents of young children is the most important contextual instruction because public health communication is always designed for a specific channel with specific constraints, and the constraint that the core call to action must land within three seconds before the screen changes imposes a creative discipline that eliminates every approach except the most immediately arresting — a message that builds to its point over four sentences will never complete its argument for most viewers. Requiring three versions for three distinct audience segments rather than one universal message is the public health communication insight that most single-poster campaigns ignore — the over-65 patient who perceives herself as healthy and low-risk requires a completely different message than the parent who will vaccinate her child the moment she learns the nasal spray is free at the practice, and a message designed to move both of them will move neither. The instruction to include one specific and memorable fact that contradicts the most common misconception held by each segment is a behavior change communication instruction grounded in the evidence on health belief models — the most effective barrier to vaccination is not lack of awareness that vaccines exist but a specific false belief that makes the vaccine seem unnecessary or risky, and a message that addresses that belief directly with a concrete contradicting fact is measurably more effective at shifting vaccination intent than a message that simply promotes the vaccine's benefits without engaging the reason the viewer has been declining it."
