  "keywords": "rewrite,LinkedIn thought leadership,preserve data,conversational tone",

  "correctAnswer": "Please rewrite the corporate article I have pasted below into a conversational LinkedIn thought-leadership post. Keep every specific number, statistic, and named result from the original article exactly as they appear — do not round figures, drop data points, or replace specific outcomes with vague summaries. Change the tone from formal and corporate to direct and conversational — write in first person as if a senior professional is sharing a personal insight, use short sentences and simple words, and avoid jargon, passive voice, and phrases like 'it has been observed that' or 'the organization has undertaken initiatives to'. Start the post with one punchy opening line that would stop someone from scrolling past it in a LinkedIn feed — not a question, not a statistic, but a bold observation or a surprising statement. Break the body into short paragraphs of two to three lines each so it is easy to read on a phone screen. End with one clear takeaway the reader can apply immediately and a single question that invites them to share their own experience in the comments. Keep the total post between 150 and 250 words.",

  "explanation": "A good rewriting prompt must give the AI two sets of rules that work in opposite directions at the same time — what must never change and what must change completely. The data preservation rule exists because AI models frequently paraphrase statistics into vague summaries when rewriting, turning a specific finding like '43 percent of employees reported burnout' into 'many employees are struggling', which strips the post of the credibility that makes thought-leadership content worth reading. The tone rules are equally specific because telling the AI to simply 'be conversational' is not enough — without banning passive voice, corporate jargon, and third-person framing, the rewrite often ends up sounding like a slightly friendlier version of the original. The opening line instruction matters because LinkedIn posts live or die in the first sentence — if it does not create immediate curiosity the rest of the post never gets read."
