  "keywords": "time-series forecasting,seasonality detection,confidence intervals",

  "correctAnswer": "Please perform a complete time-series forecasting analysis on the dataset I have pasted below which contains monthly sales figures for the past three years. Divide the analysis into four parts and complete each one before moving to the next. For data preparation, check the dataset for missing values and explain how each gap should be handled — whether to interpolate, forward fill, or flag it as too large a gap to fill reliably — then check whether the series is stationary by describing the trend and variance visually and explain whether differencing or transformation is needed before forecasting can begin. For seasonality detection, identify whether the data contains seasonal patterns by examining whether the same months consistently perform higher or lower than the annual average, state the seasonal period such as 12 for monthly data with annual seasonality, quantify the seasonal effect by showing the average percentage deviation for each month from the overall mean, and explain whether the seasonality is additive meaning it adds a fixed amount above the trend or multiplicative meaning it scales proportionally with the trend level. For the forecast, apply an appropriate forecasting model for this data — if seasonality is present use a model that handles it explicitly such as SARIMA or Facebook Prophet — generate a 6-month forward forecast, and for each forecasted month provide the point estimate, the 80 percent confidence interval, and the 95 percent confidence interval. Explain in plain language what the confidence intervals mean so a non-statistician can understand — for example that there is a 95 percent probability the actual value will fall within the wider band. For forecast evaluation, calculate the MAPE and RMSE on a holdout period of the last 6 months of historical data, explain what each metric means and whether the error level is acceptable for business planning purposes, and identify the two months where the forecast error was largest and explain what might have caused the deviation.",

  "explanation": "A good time-series forecasting prompt must structure the analysis into preparation, seasonality detection, forecasting, and evaluation as separate steps — because skipping the preparation step produces forecasts built on non-stationary data that violate the assumptions of most forecasting models, and skipping evaluation produces a forecast with no indication of whether it can actually be trusted for decision-making. The seasonality detection instruction requires quantifying the deviation per period rather than just confirming whether seasonality exists, because a business planning team needs to know that December is typically 40 percent above the annual average — not just that December is a peak month. The confidence interval instruction requires both 80 percent and 95 percent bands because a single interval without context is difficult to interpret, and explaining the intervals in plain language is essential because the most common failure in data analysis communication is producing statistically correct output that the decision-maker cannot act on. The MAPE and RMSE evaluation on a holdout period is the only honest way to assess forecast quality — a model that fits historical data perfectly but fails on the holdout period is overfit and should not be used for planning regardless of how good the in-sample metrics look."
