   {
  "id": "da_p10",
  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Create a prompt that evaluates dataset limitations and identifies potential risks in decision-making.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "dataset limitations,risk analysis,decision-making impact",

  "correctAnswer": "Please evaluate the dataset I have pasted below and produce a complete limitations and risk assessment before this data is used to make any business decisions. Divide the assessment into four parts and complete each one separately. For data quality evaluation, check for missing values in every column and report the percentage of missing data for each — flag any column where more than 10 percent of values are missing as unreliable for analysis, check for duplicate rows and explain whether they represent genuine repeated events or data entry errors that should be removed, and identify any column where the range of values contains obvious errors such as a negative age, a revenue figure of zero for an active account, or a date that falls outside the expected collection period. For representation and bias assessment, identify whether the dataset covers the full population the business wants to make decisions about or only a subset — for example if the data contains only customers from one city but the decision will affect customers nationally, name this gap explicitly and explain how it could cause the analysis to produce recommendations that work for the sampled group but fail for the broader population. Check whether any demographic or behavioural group appears underrepresented compared to its real-world proportion and explain what decisions could be distorted as a result. For temporal limitations, check whether the data is recent enough to reflect current conditions — if the dataset is more than 12 months old, identify which variables are most likely to have changed since collection and explain how acting on outdated values for those variables could lead to a wrong decision. For decision-making risk summary, produce a prioritized list of every limitation found ranked from highest to lowest risk, and for each one write a one-sentence statement of the specific wrong decision a business could make if they ignored that limitation.",

  "explanation": "A good dataset limitations prompt must treat data quality, representation bias, and temporal relevance as separate concerns — because a dataset can pass a basic quality check with no missing values and no duplicates while still being deeply misleading if it only represents a subset of the relevant population or was collected during an unusual period that no longer reflects current conditions. The 10 percent missing data threshold gives the AI a concrete cutoff rather than a subjective judgment about what counts as unreliable, which prevents the output from flagging every minor gap as a critical problem while ignoring columns that are genuinely too incomplete to use. The representation bias section is the most commonly skipped part of data limitation assessments and the most consequential — a model trained on data that underrepresents a particular customer segment will produce recommendations that actively harm that segment, and the business will have no warning because the overall accuracy metrics will still look acceptable. The decision-making risk summary ranked by severity is the most practically useful output because a data analyst who hands a stakeholder a list of ten equally weighted limitations produces paralysis rather than clarity — knowing which limitation could cause a five million rupee misallocation versus which one introduces a minor rounding uncertainty makes the assessment immediately actionable."
}
