  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Design a prompt that performs cohort analysis to identify customer retention patterns over 12 months.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "cohort analysis,customer retention,12 months",

  "correctAnswer": "Please perform a complete cohort analysis on the customer transaction dataset I have pasted below to identify retention patterns over 12 months. Divide the analysis into four parts and complete each one before moving to the next. For cohort construction, group customers by the month they made their first purchase — each group becomes one cohort identified by its acquisition month — then for each cohort track how many customers returned to make at least one additional purchase in each of the following 12 months and express this as a retention rate percentage rather than a raw count so cohorts of different sizes can be compared fairly. Present the results as a 12-column retention matrix where each row is an acquisition cohort and each column represents months 1 through 12 after first purchase, and highlight the three cohorts with the highest month-3 retention rate and the three with the lowest so the pattern is immediately visible. For retention pattern analysis, identify the month number where the average retention rate across all cohorts drops most sharply — this is the critical churn point where the business is losing the most customers — and identify whether retention stabilizes after a certain month indicating a loyal customer base that is unlikely to churn further. For cohort comparison, compare the earliest three cohorts against the most recent three cohorts and state whether retention has improved, declined, or stayed flat over time — if it has changed, identify which specific month in the retention curve changed most and suggest one possible business or product reason that could explain the shift. For business recommendations, calculate the average customer lifetime in months across all cohorts, identify the acquisition month that produced the highest 12-month retention and suggest what marketing or product conditions during that period might explain the stronger performance, and state one specific intervention the business could make at the critical churn point identified earlier to reduce dropout at that stage.",

  "explanation": "A good cohort analysis prompt must define exactly how cohorts are constructed, how retention is measured, and what the output format looks like — because a vague instruction like 'perform cohort analysis' produces inconsistent groupings, raw counts instead of percentages, and a flat table that makes it impossible to spot patterns without additional work. Expressing retention as a percentage rather than a raw count is the single most important formatting decision in cohort analysis — a cohort of 500 customers with 100 returning in month 3 has the same 20 percent retention as a cohort of 50 customers with 10 returning, but the raw counts make them look completely different and lead to incorrect conclusions about which cohort performed better. The critical churn point identification is the most actionable output of a cohort analysis because it tells the business exactly which moment in the customer lifecycle needs the most attention — a retention intervention placed at month 2 when the real drop happens at month 5 wastes resources and produces no measurable improvement. Comparing early cohorts against recent ones is essential for understanding whether the business is getting better or worse at retaining customers over time, which is a question no single-cohort snapshot can answer."
