  "text": "Design a prompt that evaluates risks and limitations of a forecasting model including assumption sensitivity analysis.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "forecasting model risks,limitations,sensitivity analysis",

  "correctAnswer": "Please evaluate the risks and limitations of the forecasting model and its output I have pasted below, and perform a sensitivity analysis on its key assumptions. Divide the evaluation into four parts and complete each one before moving to the next. For model assumption audit, list every assumption the model makes explicitly — for example that the historical trend will continue, that seasonality patterns will repeat, that no external shocks will occur, or that the relationships between variables remain stable — and for each assumption state whether there is evidence in the historical data that supports it or whether it is being taken on faith without verification. For limitation assessment, identify the three most significant limitations of this specific model for this specific use case — do not list generic forecasting limitations but ones that apply directly to the data and the decision being made — and for each limitation explain the specific wrong decision a business could make if they treated the forecast as certain rather than as an estimate with uncertainty. For sensitivity analysis, identify the two or three input assumptions the forecast is most sensitive to by changing each one by plus 10 percent and minus 10 percent while holding all others constant, report how much the forecast output changes for each adjustment, and rank the assumptions from most to least sensitive so the business knows which variables to monitor most closely in real time. For risk summary, produce a plain-language risk statement for each scenario — best case, base case, and worst case — by applying optimistic and pessimistic versions of the most sensitive assumptions together, state the forecast output under each scenario as a specific number rather than a range, and end with one sentence telling the decision-maker what single early warning signal they should watch for that would indicate the base case forecast is no longer valid.",

  "explanation": "A good forecasting risk evaluation prompt must require assumption-specific sensitivity analysis rather than generic uncertainty statements — because telling a business that a forecast has uncertainty is useless without showing them which assumptions drive the most variance and by how much. The assumption audit step is critical because most forecasting models carry implicit assumptions that were never explicitly stated during model building, and a business that acts on a forecast without knowing those assumptions has no way to recognize when conditions have changed enough to invalidate the prediction. The sensitivity analysis instruction requires changing each assumption by a fixed percentage rather than asking for a qualitative assessment, because a quantitative result — the forecast drops by 18 percent if advertising spend falls 10 percent — is directly actionable for budget planning while a statement like 'the forecast is sensitive to advertising spend' produces no decision. The three-scenario risk summary with specific numbers rather than ranges is the most important output for a non-technical decision-maker because ranges invite the optimism bias of assuming the actual outcome will land near the top — presenting a specific worst-case number forces the stakeholder to confront the downside concretely rather than abstractly."
