   {
  "id": "e_p10",
  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Create a prompt that evaluates a student's essay using predefined rubric criteria and provides structured feedback.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "evaluate essay,rubric criteria,structured feedback",

  "correctAnswer": "Please evaluate the Grade 10 student essay I have pasted below using the four rubric criteria listed here and provide structured feedback that the student can read and act on before their next draft. For each criterion, give a score out of 5, write two to three sentences explaining the reasoning behind that score using specific evidence from the essay rather than general impressions, and write one concrete improvement instruction that tells the student exactly what to change and how — do not write feedback like 'improve your argument' but instead write 'your second paragraph makes a claim about climate change without any supporting evidence — add one specific statistic or named example to make this point convincing'. The four criteria are as follows. For argument clarity, assess whether the essay has one central thesis stated in the introduction that every body paragraph directly supports — if the thesis is missing, vague, or contradicted by any paragraph, quote the specific sentence that causes the problem and suggest a rewrite. For evidence and support, assess whether every major claim in the essay is backed by a specific fact, statistic, or example rather than a general statement — identify the two weakest claims in the essay and explain exactly what kind of evidence would strengthen each one. For structure and coherence, assess whether the essay flows logically from introduction to body to conclusion, whether each paragraph has a clear topic sentence, and whether transitions between paragraphs connect ideas rather than just moving from one point to the next — quote any transition that feels abrupt and suggest a replacement. For language and expression, assess whether the vocabulary is appropriate for Grade 10 level, whether sentences vary in length and structure, and whether there are any grammatical errors that affect meaning — list no more than three specific errors with corrections so the feedback is focused rather than overwhelming. End with one overall strength the student should carry into their next piece of writing and one priority improvement that will have the biggest impact on their score.",

  "explanation": "A good essay evaluation prompt must define the rubric criteria explicitly within the prompt rather than asking the AI to apply generic standards — because different teachers, schools, and assignments prioritize different qualities, and an AI that invents its own rubric produces feedback that may be irrelevant to what the student is actually being assessed on. Requiring evidence from the essay for every score justification prevents the AI from producing feedback that could apply to any essay — a student who reads 'your argument needs more support' learns nothing, while a student who reads 'your third paragraph claims that social media causes depression but provides no study, statistic, or example to support this' knows exactly which sentence to fix and what kind of addition is needed. The limit of three grammar corrections is a deliberate constraint because overwhelming a student with twenty corrections produces anxiety rather than improvement — identifying the three errors that most affect meaning gives the student a focused editing task they can complete successfully, which builds the habit of self-correction more effectively than an exhaustive error list. The final strength and priority improvement structure ensures the feedback ends with both encouragement and direction, which is the combination most likely to motivate a student to engage with the feedback rather than reading the score and discarding the rest."
}
