    {
  "id": "f_p10",
  "type": "prompt-writing",
  "text": "Create a prompt that audits a fashion brand's campaign for tone consistency, trend alignment, sustainability messaging, and conversion effectiveness.",
  "options": [],
  "correctIndex": -1,
  "keywords": "campaign audit, tone consistency, trend alignment, sustainability, conversion",
  "correctAnswer": "Conduct a detailed audit of the following fashion brand campaign across four critical dimensions. For tone consistency, evaluate whether the language, personality, and emotional register of the campaign stays the same across every touchpoint — including the campaign tagline, product descriptions, social media captions, email copy, and any paid ad copy — because a campaign that sounds confident and editorial on Instagram but corporate and flat in its email marketing creates a fractured brand experience that erodes customer trust. Identify any specific moments where the tone shifts or feels inconsistent and explain exactly what needs to change to bring those touchpoints back into alignment. For trend alignment, assess whether the campaign's visual direction, language, and cultural references feel current and relevant to the fashion moment the brand is trying to own — identify whether the campaign is leading a trend, riding an existing trend at the right time, or arriving late to a trend that has already peaked, and explain what that means for how the campaign will be received by its target audience. For sustainability messaging, evaluate whether the brand's environmental and ethical claims are specific, credible, and backed by tangible actions — flag any language that sounds like greenwashing, which is when a brand uses vague sustainability terms like 'eco-friendly' or 'conscious collection' without explaining what those terms actually mean in practice, because today's fashion consumers are highly educated about greenwashing and will lose trust in a brand that cannot back up its claims. For conversion effectiveness, assess whether every piece of campaign content has a clear and logical next step for the customer — evaluate the strength of the calls-to-action, whether the campaign creates enough desire and urgency to motivate a purchase, and whether the journey from campaign content to the product page is smooth and frictionless. End the audit with an overall campaign health score out of 10 for each dimension and a prioritized list of the top 5 changes that would have the biggest positive impact on the campaign's performance.",
  "explanation": "A fashion campaign audit is one of the most valuable but most underused tools in brand management because most brands only evaluate their campaigns on surface-level metrics like reach and engagement, without assessing the deeper strategic and creative qualities that determine whether a campaign actually builds brand equity and drives sales over time. Tone consistency is the dimension most brands overlook because it requires evaluating every single touchpoint of a campaign together rather than in isolation — a social media team, a copywriter, and an email marketer can each individually produce good work that collectively creates a confusing and inconsistent brand voice. Trend alignment is especially critical in fashion because the industry moves faster than almost any other, and a campaign that feels even slightly out of step with the cultural moment can make an entire brand feel irrelevant overnight. The sustainability dimension requires particular care in this audit because greenwashing has become one of the most serious reputational risks in the fashion industry — consumers and regulators are increasingly holding brands accountable for vague environmental claims, and a campaign that uses sustainability language without substance can do more damage to a brand than not mentioning sustainability at all. The conversion effectiveness dimension is what connects the creative quality of the campaign to its commercial purpose — a campaign can be visually stunning and culturally relevant but still fail to drive sales if the calls-to-action are weak, the customer journey is confusing, or the campaign creates desire without giving the customer a clear and easy path to purchase. The overall health score for each dimension gives the brand a simple and comparable way to see at a glance where their campaign is strongest and where it needs the most urgent attention."
}
